31
00:02:46,057 --> 00:02:51,541
The first one is Upward and Click, which was written by Douglas Adams in the 90s.

32
00:02:53,069 --> 00:03:01,111
Facade is probably the most famous chatbot game, and it's very interesting, and we'll speak a bit about it later in this talk.

33
00:03:01,891 --> 00:03:10,614
The third chatbot game here is a flash game that you can find for free on the internet, and which has very similar themes to EventZero.

34
00:03:12,240 --> 00:03:15,082
I like to classify games this way.

35
00:03:16,123 --> 00:03:19,946
You have first the good old system games like Super Mario,

36
00:03:20,427 --> 00:03:23,269
and these games basically work like that.

37
00:03:23,389 --> 00:03:26,412
You push a button, your avatar performs an action,

38
00:03:26,932 --> 00:03:29,754
and this action has impact on the game system.

39
00:03:30,335 --> 00:03:33,718
And all of this is constant.

40
00:03:34,098 --> 00:03:35,879
The action will always be the same,

41
00:03:35,899 --> 00:03:39,102
and the impact will always be the same.

42
00:03:39,962 --> 00:03:41,624
And then you have semantic games.

43
00:03:42,164 --> 00:03:45,047
And semantic games don't work because of a combination

44
00:03:45,608 --> 00:03:47,570
of gears of your game system.

45
00:03:47,710 --> 00:03:49,572
It doesn't work because of that.

46
00:03:50,092 --> 00:03:55,738
But semantic games are based on a huge database.

47
00:03:56,465 --> 00:03:58,646
which have been written by game designers.

48
00:03:59,106 --> 00:04:00,727
And if we take for example Scribblenauts,

49
00:04:01,208 --> 00:04:03,589
Scribblenauts is a game where you can type words

50
00:04:03,909 --> 00:04:06,591
and these words appear in your game level.

51
00:04:06,891 --> 00:04:08,612
For example if you type plane,

52
00:04:08,712 --> 00:04:10,293
there will be a plane in your level

53
00:04:10,413 --> 00:04:12,995
and the player will be able to interact with this plane.

54
00:04:13,615 --> 00:04:15,196
as with a real plane.

55
00:04:15,776 --> 00:04:19,618
And the system is not able to understand what a plane is

56
00:04:19,638 --> 00:04:20,958
and to generate it.

57
00:04:21,319 --> 00:04:25,701
It has to be based on a database

58
00:04:26,141 --> 00:04:29,423
where the game designer had to explain what a plane was.

59
00:04:30,503 --> 00:04:32,824
Chatbot games are semantic games.

60
00:04:32,844 --> 00:04:36,026
They are just a subcategory of it.

61
00:04:36,786 --> 00:04:41,068
And as semantic games, it depends mostly on the database.

62
00:04:42,201 --> 00:04:46,804
It's important to understand that chatbot games are not text adventure games.

63
00:04:47,424 --> 00:04:51,387
You know, these kind of games that were very popular in the 80s.

64
00:04:53,068 --> 00:04:58,611
In such games like Zork, for example, the player has to type an action and a target

65
00:04:58,871 --> 00:05:00,452
to progress in the adventure.

66
00:05:00,512 --> 00:05:04,434
For example, you can type open door and it will probably open the door.

67
00:05:05,575 --> 00:05:12,137
And the challenge here is to guess what is a good action and a good target.

68
00:05:12,557 --> 00:05:14,297
So basically they are kind of riddles.

69
00:05:15,778 --> 00:05:20,239
But chatbot games focus more on the natural language part.

70
00:05:21,019 --> 00:05:28,542
In chatbot games you have to talk in plain English to a character and a roleplay.

71
00:05:29,162 --> 00:05:31,382
So for me text adventure games...

72
00:05:33,799 --> 00:05:36,041
works on a more rational part of the brain

73
00:05:36,462 --> 00:05:41,707
when chatbot games work with a more emotional part of the brain.

74
00:05:43,588 --> 00:05:49,654
So now that all of that has been stated, what I suggest is with this talk

75
00:05:49,834 --> 00:05:52,396
giving you some cues to make your own chatbot game.

76
00:05:54,919 --> 00:05:57,241
At first we have to start with the basics.

77
00:05:58,469 --> 00:06:04,551
When you want to work on a chatbot game, as every other kind of game, you have to define what is your game experience.

78
00:06:05,152 --> 00:06:11,434
And it's important to understand that the experience of chatbot games is basically narrative.

79
00:06:11,974 --> 00:06:21,298
Chatbot games are narrative games, story-driven games, and you have to understand that to write efficiently your chatbot.

80
00:06:22,479 --> 00:06:27,682
Chatbots are characters like any other character, like in any other kind of fiction.

81
00:06:28,042 --> 00:06:30,944
And you have to ask yourself some questions like,

82
00:06:31,424 --> 00:06:33,005
what is your chatbot motivation?

83
00:06:33,485 --> 00:06:34,025
Who made it?

84
00:06:34,505 --> 00:06:35,946
Can he or she feel things?

85
00:06:36,607 --> 00:06:38,868
Express love, anxiety, jealousy?

86
00:06:39,688 --> 00:06:41,309
How does it change through the story arc?

87
00:06:42,049 --> 00:06:44,471
What relationships can the player build with it?

88
00:06:45,451 --> 00:06:49,513
And more importantly, what do your chatbot know?

89
00:06:50,474 --> 00:06:54,977
and what does it... don't know basically.

90
00:06:55,277 --> 00:06:58,239
If you can define this, it will be much easier for you

91
00:06:58,780 --> 00:07:01,021
to write for chatbot.

92
00:07:01,722 --> 00:07:04,764
Not only because you will be able to have...

93
00:07:05,523 --> 00:07:07,825
better lines and a better story arc.

94
00:07:08,145 --> 00:07:11,887
But also because you won't fall in the trap of the sentient AI

95
00:07:12,568 --> 00:07:15,210
and you will be able to accept as a writer

96
00:07:15,650 --> 00:07:17,812
that your chatbot doesn't know anything

97
00:07:18,532 --> 00:07:22,995
and there are reasons for that and the player will be able to understand that

98
00:07:23,696 --> 00:07:25,617
and won't have problem with that.

99
00:07:27,687 --> 00:07:34,058
This was on the narrative part, but of course chatbots are systems and you have to build

100
00:07:34,078 --> 00:07:38,665
a working system which supports your writing.

101
00:07:39,427 --> 00:07:40,088
And generally...

102
00:07:42,111 --> 00:07:49,495
Today we all use chatbots basically, or at least we know them because we have our smartphones

103
00:07:49,555 --> 00:07:54,998
with their assistants like Siri, there is no Cortana on Windows, and these chatbots

104
00:07:55,258 --> 00:08:01,702
are very efficient but they use very complex systems like neural networks, machine learnings

105
00:08:01,842 --> 00:08:02,803
and all these kind of things.

106
00:08:03,423 --> 00:08:07,765
But the problem with that is the systems are basically black boxes.

107
00:08:08,145 --> 00:08:13,308
They work with an input and an output, but you cannot really dive into them and tweak

108
00:08:13,348 --> 00:08:14,108
the little details.

109
00:08:14,569 --> 00:08:18,010
And you know that us game designers are kind of control freaks.

110
00:08:18,491 --> 00:08:22,553
We like to be able to master everything in the experience.

111
00:08:22,813 --> 00:08:25,874
And it's very important on a narrative game.

112
00:08:26,475 --> 00:08:28,256
So my advice here is...

113
00:08:29,136 --> 00:08:37,460
just make a simple system, a deterministic system that you will be able to write for and to debug, to fully understand.

114
00:08:38,100 --> 00:08:44,623
And your chatbot won't be efficient because of its code, but because of its writing.

115
00:08:45,103 --> 00:08:51,045
Because as I was telling you, yes, the database is the most important part of it.

116
00:08:52,046 --> 00:08:55,307
And for example, what you see on this slide is the first version of Event0.

117
00:08:56,067 --> 00:08:58,248
Event0 starts as a paper prototype.

118
00:08:59,577 --> 00:09:05,002
And the first playtest of the game, where Sergei Mohov, the game designer of the game, and I,

119
00:09:05,403 --> 00:09:08,266
sitting at a table and basically running a D&D session.

120
00:09:08,746 --> 00:09:12,230
We were explaining to the player, OK, this is the context, you are in a spaceship,

121
00:09:12,330 --> 00:09:14,633
there is a computer in front of you, what do you type?

122
00:09:15,113 --> 00:09:18,977
And then we are giving them a paper and the height to write down the query.

123
00:09:19,868 --> 00:09:22,468
And with us, we had a flowchart with the AI,

124
00:09:23,068 --> 00:09:24,689
and we were following this flowchart.

125
00:09:24,849 --> 00:09:27,629
And without cheating, we were generating an answer

126
00:09:27,809 --> 00:09:28,429
for this player.

127
00:09:29,130 --> 00:09:31,850
And we performed this kind of playtest dozens

128
00:09:32,110 --> 00:09:32,930
and dozens of times.

129
00:09:33,330 --> 00:09:36,631
And we discovered how to handle questions or insults.

130
00:09:37,511 --> 00:09:41,592
And at the end, we had a much more efficient flowchart.

131
00:09:42,452 --> 00:09:45,633
We came to our programmer team and said, OK, this is our AI.

132
00:09:46,293 --> 00:09:49,373
Implement it as you want, but it has to work like this.

133
00:09:50,866 --> 00:09:57,630
Fun anecdote on that is that we figured out that our players were kind of shy when they were writing things in front of us

134
